\cb5 Two items of evidence (the prospectors\'92 collisions with the spaceships) each confirm the hypothesis that there will be an annihilation, even though the observations together refute it. I prefer to call this an irony rather than a paradox, for there is no doubt that such strange turns of affairs can exist.\cb1 \
\
\cb6 The peculiarity is partly semantic. The verb \'93confirm\'94 is used in two ways.\cb1 \
\
\cb5 In everyday speech, we almost always use \'93confirm\'94 in the absolute sense, to mean that something is clinched; established beyond reasonable doubt. \'93The boss confirmed that Sandra got the raise\'94 means that, whatever the doubts beforehand, it is now just about 100 percent certain that Sandra got the raise.\cb1 \
\
\cb5 Scientists and confirmation theorists often use \'93confirm\'94 in the incremental sense. To confirm incrementally is to \'93provide evidence for\'94 or \'93increase the probability of.\'94 We speak of probabilities because confirmation of a generalization is always tentative.\cb1 \
\
