\cb5 Not only should a new theory account for the successful predictions of the theory it would replace. It should offer new, different predictions of its own. In Karl Popper\'92s terms, the new theory must have greater \'93empirical content.\'94 It must make more testable predictions in more realms of experience than the old theory.\cb1 \
\
\cb2 A new theory should be more open to possible refutation, not less. If there is one thing that is a dead giveaway for a crank theory, it is that the theory has been modified to restrict its own refutation. An honest hypothesis is open to being disproven. \cb1 \
\
